                                <h1>Stableford Scoring: All You Need To Kno=
w | Eynesbury Golf</h1>
                                <div class=3D"article-details">
                                                                        <di=
v class=3D"article-details__date">July 17, 2023</div>
                                </div>
                                <div class=3D"editor-content">
                                    <h1>Our Stableford Scoring Guide!</h1>
<p>When you=E2=80=99re out on the links, you=E2=80=99re probably playing by=
 the rules of =E2=80=98stroke play=E2=80=99 =E2=80=93 you count your total =
strokes at each hole, add them up, and whoever has the lowest total at the =
end wins. But did you know there are other fun ways to count your score?</p=
>
<p>In this guide, we=E2=80=99ll run through the keys to understanding Stabl=
eford scoring, an alternative scoring system that is a great way to inject =
some novelty into your next round of golf. So next time you=E2=80=99re out =
enjoying our beautiful <a href=3D"https://eynesburygolf.com.au/the-course/"=
>Eynesbury Golf Course</a>, we recommend giving Stableford scoring a try.</=
p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"alignnone wp-image-387=
 size-full" src=3D"https://eynesburygolf.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/=
K8A8474.jpg" alt=3D"" width=3D"2048" height=3D"1365"></p>
<h2>What Is Stableford Scoring?</h2>
<p>Stroke play rewards low scores. If, at the end of each hole, your score =
is zero or less, you=E2=80=99re doing well. In Stableford scoring, you=E2=
=80=99re looking for a high score at the end of each hole. This doesn=E2=80=
=99t mean you want to bogey intentionally, though, because the winner is th=
e player with the highest total at the end.</p>
<p>In Stableford Scoring, points are awarded depending on how many strokes =
over or under par you are, and there=E2=80=99s a ceiling on how low your sc=
ore can be each hole. So even if you have a shocker, you won=E2=80=99t be p=
unished with a terrible score. The result is that Stableford scoring doesn=
=E2=80=99t reward playing conservatively, so players feel encouraged to go =
for those miraculous shots, and games tend to be quicker. What is there to =
lose?</p>
<h3>The History Of Stableford Scoring</h3>
<p>Picture this: you=E2=80=99re humming along in your game, dropping stroke=
s at every hole. Then, out of nowhere, a triple bogey or two blemishes your=
 scorecard, and you=E2=80=99re ready to quit the whole round. This was what=
 Frank Barney Gorton Stableford was trying to avoid when he introduced his =
scoring system back in 1898.</p>
<p>While it didn=E2=80=99t catch on until the 1930s, Stableford=E2=80=99s s=
ystem found popularity because it=E2=80=99s less punitive than stroke play.=
 Eventually, professional tours like The International in Colorado and the =
American Century Championship have used the scoring system.</p>
<h2>How Does Stableford Scoring Work?</h2>
<p>Stableford scoring awards points based on the number of strokes taken co=
mpared to the par score for each hole. It=E2=80=99s not dissimilar to strok=
e play, but a good score is positive, rather than negative. For example, a =
birdie (a score of one under par) would be awarded 3 points in Stableford g=
olf scoring, while a bogey (one over par) gets one point. For two strokes o=
r more over par, the score is zero. At the end of the round, the player wit=
h the highest score is the winner.</p>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a handy list to explain Stableford scoring in golf:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>Two or more strokes over par:</str=
ong> 0 points<br>
<strong>One stroke over:</strong> 1 point<br>
<strong>Par:</strong> 2 points<br>
<strong>One stroke under:</strong> 3 points<br>
<strong>Two strokes under:</strong> 4 points<br>
<strong>Three strokes under:</strong> 5 points<br>
<strong>Four strokes under:</strong> 6 points</p>
<h3>What Are The Handicap Adjustments In Stableford Scoring?</h3>
<p>To make things a little fairer when playing with players of different sk=
ill levels, you can factor in a handicap. A player=E2=80=99s handicap is al=
located against holes based on their stroke index (a good explainer <a href=
=3D"https://www.golfmonthly.com/features/the-game/what-is-stroke-index-6526=
6"><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">here</span></a>), which will adjust th=
eir score for that hole.</p>
<p>It can get a little complicated, but essentially, players with higher ha=
ndicaps will benefit from added scores on more holes than players with lowe=
r handicaps. For example, a player with a handicap of 18 would receive an a=
djusted score on 18 holes, while a player with a handicap of 5 would receiv=
e adjusted scores on 5 holes. What that adjustment is will be determined by=
 the hole=E2=80=99s score index.</p>
<h2>What Is A Modified Stableford?</h2>
<p>When used in professional matches, there is a tweaked version called =E2=
=80=98Modified Stableford=E2=80=99 that encourages more aggressive play. It=
s score system looks like this:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>Two or more strokes over par:</str=
ong> -3 points<br>
<strong>One stroke over:</strong> -1 point<br>
<strong>Par:</strong> 0 points<br>
<strong>One stroke under:</strong> 2 points<br>
<strong>Two strokes under:</strong> 5 points<br>
<strong>Three strokes under:</strong> 8 points</p>
<h2>What Are The Benefits Of Using Stableford Scoring?</h2>
<p>There are plenty of reasons to use Stableford scoring. Here are a few of=
 the biggest incentives:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>It=E2=80=99s fun:</strong> Stableford offers regular golfers so=
me novelty and excitement. Maybe you=E2=80=99ve mastered stroke play and ar=
e ready for a new challenge (we=E2=80=99d be happy to take some tips, in th=
at case!) or are just keen on seeing golf in a different way.</li>
<li><strong>There=E2=80=99s a safety net:</strong> This is why Frank Stable=
ford invented the system in the first place. If you=E2=80=99re halfway thro=
ugh a round and suddenly spend six shots in the sand, it won=E2=80=99t ruin=
 your whole game. There=E2=80=99s a minimum score per hole no matter how ma=
ny shots you take, which means the average Stableford score for a tough hol=
e is a lot better than in stroke play.</li>
<li><strong>Positive play is rewarded:</strong> Because there=E2=80=99s a l=
imit on self-inflicted damage, there=E2=80=99s an incentive to play ambitio=
usly. Think you can make that 20ft putt? Want to chip over the lake? Go for=
 it!</li>
<li><strong>Everyone can play:</strong> Tough courses or friends with low h=
andicaps can be difficult to play with if you=E2=80=99re not up to the leve=
l, but Stableford scoring is a great equaliser. Anyone can win on their day=
.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Tips and Strategies For Stableford Scoring</h2>
<p>Playing well at Stableford Scoring golf requires most of the same techni=
cal skills as stroke play but there are still a few things to keep in mind =
if you want to do well:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Play with purpose:</strong> While you can still do yourself in =
with consistently bad shot selection, Stableford is a type of golf that rew=
ards positive play. You have to be in it to win it, so try for those riskie=
r shots.</li>
<li><strong>Know your handicap adjustments:</strong> Some holes will adjust=
 your score based on your handicap and the hole=E2=80=99s scoring index. Kn=
owing which holes are friendly to you, score-wise, can allow you to take st=
rategic risks.</li>
<li><strong>Enjoy it:</strong> It=E2=80=99s always good to remember why we =
play golf: for the love of it. Stableford Scoring is a great variation on t=
he classic game we all love, so take it with good humour and enjoy yourself=
 out there.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Enjoy Your Friendly Matches At Eynesbury Golf!</h2>
<p>Stableford Scoring can be a lot of fun for new players and professionals=
 alike. Whether you=E2=80=99re looking for a new challenge, a casual round =
with friends or just keen to find out what all the fuss is about, why not c=
ome by for a game? At Eynesbury Golf Course, you=E2=80=99ll find 18 pristin=
e holes surrounded by the gorgeous countryside.</p>
<p>Are you keen to pay us a visit or want to learn more about Stableford Sc=
oring? <a href=3D"https://eynesburygolf.com.au/contact-us/"><span style=3D"=
font-weight: 400;">Get in contact</span></a> with our friendly team today.<=
/p>
